# Auto-absorbed by hexa loop --dfs (RFC 080 Phase L)
# cycle 0 · 6 verified DFS children

@P perfect_code_ratio_correspondence :: dfs [3?]
  <- sigma, tau
  => "Test whether sigma(n)/tau(n) equals the minimum Hamming distance d of a perfect code with length n across the known perfect code family: the Hamming codes [2^r-1, 2^r-1-r, 3], the binary Golay [23,12,7], and the ternary Golay [11,6,5]. Compute the ratio at n=23, n=11, n=15, n=31 and compare to d=7, 5, 3, 3 respectively. If the ratio fails to match d outside n=6 (which corresponds to the [7,4,3] code shifted by one), the n=6 coincidence is numerical; if it tracks d in any nontrivial second case, structural correspondence is plausible."

@P divisor_ratio_three_classification :: dfs [3?]
  <- sigma, tau
  => "Characterize all n for which sigma(n)/tau(n) = 3 exactly, and check whether this set has any arithmetic or combinatorial overlap with parameters of perfect codes or Steiner systems. Since sigma(n)/tau(n) is the arithmetic mean of divisors, ratio = 3 forces a tight divisor structure (e.g. n=6, and candidates among small composites). If the solution set is finite or sparse and disjoint from perfect-code lengths beyond n=6, the parent coincidence reduces to the single accident at n=6 rather than a family-level structural identity."

@P n_phi_n_equals_tau_n_classification :: dfs [3?]
  <- phi, n
  => "Test whether n - phi(n) = tau(n) holds only for n = 1, 4, 6 or extends further. For n = 1: 1 - 1 = 0 vs tau(1) = 1, fails. For n = 4: 4 - 2 = 2 = tau(4), holds. For n = 6: 6 - 2 = 4 = tau(6), holds. For n = 8: 8 - 4 = 4 = tau(8), holds. For n = 9: 9 - 6 = 3 = tau(9), holds. Enumerate n up to 10^4, conjecture that solutions are exactly {4, 6, 8, 9, p^2 for small p, 2p for small p}, and search for the largest counterexample-free range."

@P prime_power_subfamily_n_minus_phi :: dfs [3?]
  <- phi
  => "Restrict the equation n - phi(n) = tau(n) to prime powers n = p^k. Then n - phi(n) = p^(k-1) and tau(n) = k+1, giving p^(k-1) = k+1. Solve: (p=2,k=1) gives 1=2 fail; (p=2,k=2) gives 2=3 fail; (p=2,k=3) gives 4=4 holds (n=8); (p=3,k=2) gives 3=3 holds (n=9); (p=3,k=3) gives 9=4 fail. Prove that n=8 and n=9 are the only prime-power solutions, and characterize the semiprime 2p subfamily separately."

@P n10_sopfr_counterexample :: dfs [3?]
  <- sopfr, n
  => "For n = 10 = 2 · 5, sopfr(10) = 7, but the smallest prime not dividing 10 is 3, and the smallest prime strictly above the largest prime factor 5 is 7. Investigate whether the parent conjecture conflates two distinct quantities: \"smallest prime not dividing n\" versus \"smallest prime above max prime factor.\" Test square-free n ∈ {6, 10, 14, 15, 21, 22, 30, 35} and tabulate sopfr(n) against both candidate formulas. Predict the conjecture fails for any square-free n with a prime gap inside its factor set (e.g., n = 15 = 3 · 5 gives sopfr = 8, neither 2 nor 7)."

@P sopfr_squarefree_lower_bound :: dfs [3?]
  <- sopfr, n
  => "Rather than equality, probe the inequality sopfr(n) ≥ p_next(n) for square-free n, where p_next is the smallest prime exceeding the largest prime factor. Stress-test across square-free n up to 100, recording when equality holds (suspect: only n = 6 and primorial-adjacent cases) versus strict inequality. Determine whether equality characterizes a finite or sparse set, and whether sopfr(n) − p_next(n) admits a clean expression in terms of omega(n) or the prime-gap structure of factors. This reframes the parent from a doomed equality into a possibly tight bound with a characterizable equality locus."

